description: Anglo-Norman and Old French estoper, from a Late Latin verb, from Classical Latin stuppa (“oakum”).

verbs.description: estop (third-person singular simple present estops, present participle estopping, simple past and past participle estopped)

entries.meaning: To impede or bar by estoppel.
examples: ...we twitted them, while we were together in the sun of the Continent, about English heating habits. Having done that, we are now estopped from bringing the matter up.
